<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-306-676  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 306 676.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  June 1989 v10 n6 p50(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An approach to measuring nursing care quality.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Freund, Louis E.; MacArthur, Anne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Healthcare executives are constantly concerned as to how toimprove the quality of nursing care.andP;  Computer-based systems areoften seen as the solution for speeding workflow, increasingaccessibility and reducing error potential.andP;  Systems are acceptedoften simply to reduce costs to achieve patient care objectives orfor improved service to physicians.andP;  Installing a system orinstituting a procedure to eliminate the need for transcription ofhandwritten notes can profoundly affect the accuracy of patientcharts.andP;  Measurement strategies fall into two categories: thosebased on results of nursing care and those based on observations.andO;A six-step procedure that is useful in designing and conductingstudies to assess the impact of new technology on nursing carequality is described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     NursingQuality ControlTechnologyHealth CareMeasurement Techniques.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>